<p><strong>"The Great Partition: The Making of India and Pakistan" by Yasmin Khan</strong></p>
<p><strong>Q: What is the main focus of Yasmin Khan's book, "The Great Partition"?</strong></p>
<p>A: "The Great Partition" chronicles the violent and chaotic division of India into two independent nations, India and Pakistan, in 1947. Khan explores the historical, religious, and political factors that led to this momentous event, as well as its devastating human consequences.</p>
<p><strong>Q: How does Khan describe the human impact of the Partition?</strong></p>
<p>A: Khan paints a vivid picture of the mass migration, violence, and trauma experienced by millions of people during the Partition. She documents the horrific acts of violence against religious minorities and the immense suffering endured by refugees and displaced persons.</p>
<p><strong>Q: What were the underlying causes of the Partition?</strong></p>
<p>A: According to Khan, a complex web of factors contributed to the Partition, including British colonial policies, the rise of nationalism, and the deep-seated religious and cultural divisions between Hindus and Muslims. The book explores the political machinations and ideological debates that shaped the decision to divide India.</p>
<p><strong>Q: How has Khan's work on the Partition been received?</strong></p>
<p>A: "The Great Partition" has been widely acclaimed for its rigorous scholarship and its empathy for the people affected by the Partition. It has received numerous awards and accolades, including the James Tait Black Memorial Prize for Biography and the US National Book Critics Circle Award.</p>
<p><strong>Q: What are the broader implications of Khan's research on the Partition?</strong></p>
<p>A: Khan's study of the Partition sheds light on the challenges of nation-building, the dangers of religious and ethnic extremism, and the ongoing legacy of conflict in South Asia. It is a valuable resource for understanding the complex history of a region that continues to be affected by its colonial past.</p>